// Orishas — the 12 canonical Yoruba deities — SEO funnel.
// /gab44/orishas (index) + /gab44/orishas/{slug}.
//
// First Afro-diasporic pantheon on gab44. Peer to Olympians, Norse, Hindu Devas,
// Egyptian, Celtic. Closes the structural gap of having no African religious
// surface despite 80+ esoteric modules. Massive diaspora SEO audience: US
// African-American spirituality, Brazilian Candomblé, Cuban Lukumí/Santería,
// Caribbean Vodou-adjacent practice, and the witchy-TikTok / "rootwork"
// crossover.
//
// Three families × 4 deities:
//  - Heads of Heaven (Obatalá, Eleguá, Aganju, Olokun) — white / black-red /
//    volcano-orange / deep-ocean indigo; the cool-headed creator, the
//    crossroads opener, the volcano-and-sun, the depths-of-the-sea.
//  - Mothers & Lovers of Water (Yemayá, Oshún, Oyá, Babalú-Ayé) — ocean blue /
//    river gold / storm purple / earth burlap; the ocean mother, the
//    river-honey lover, the cemetery-storm gatekeeper, the wounded healer.
//  - Warriors & Hunters of the Forest (Shangó, Ogún, Oshosi, Òsanyìn) —
//    thunder red-white / iron green-black / bow turquoise / herb green;
//    the thunder-king dancer, the iron-and-road warrior, the hunter-archer,
//    the one-eyed-one-armed-one-legged herbalist.
//
// Source-honest from the Ifá literary corpus (the 256 Odu — the canonical
// Yoruba divination text-system, oral-to-codified from at least the 1st
// millennium CE), the Pataki (the sacred narrative stories of the orishas),
// William Bascom's Ifa Divination (1969) and Sixteen Cowries (1980), Pierre
// Verger's Notes sur le culte des Orisa et Vodun (1957) — the foundational
// ethnographic survey, Wande Abimbola's Ifa: An Exposition of Ifa Literary
// Corpus (1976), Migene González-Wippler's Santería (1973), Lydia Cabrera's
// El Monte (1954) — the foundational Cuban Lukumí text, Robert Farris
// Thompson's Flash of the Spirit (1983), and the diaspora's living oral
// tradition through initiated babalawos and iyanifás.
//
// Shadow-honest: 19th-c. missionary suppression in Yorubaland, the Middle
// Passage rupture and Catholic-saint syncretization as survival strategy,
// 20th-c. Brazilian Candomblé persecution under Vargas, Cuban Santería
// persecution under early communism, Hollywood "voodoo" demonization that
// lumps unrelated African Traditional Religions together, the "primitive
// religion" anthropological frame (Frazer / Mary Kingsley / 19th-c. armchair
// comparativism), the modern commercial commodification by uninitiated white
// sellers (Etsy "orisha candles," Amazon "Yemaya statues," Instagram
// "babalawo" without lineage), the "spiritual but not religious"
// extraction-without-acknowledgment, the appropriation of orisha names
// onto astrology accounts that have never been to a roncó, and the silent
// flattening of the orishas into mere "African gods" that strips them of
// the *lineage requirement* that is central to the tradition.

